\chapter{Frieze Patterns}

\begin{quote}
In this universe, there's only one absolute\dots  everything freezes!

\hfill---Mr.\ Freeze
\end{quote}


\section{Design in a Line}

In design and architecture, a \index{frieze pattern}\textit{frieze}, pronounced
``freeze,'' is a horizontal band that is found near the ceiling or
roof. It is often decorated with a repeating design. Let's see some examples:
\[
\includegraphics{../graphics/fpfrieze.pdf}
\]
Frieze patterns often have symmetry in their structure. In this chapter,
we will study this symmetry. At this point we will refrain from giving
a rigorous definition of a \textit{frieze pattern}. Instead, this will
be a result of our work in this chapter.


\break

\subsection{Symmetries}

\subsection*{Translations}\index{translation}

Perhaps the most apparent symmetry that frieze patters can exhibit is
symmetry through \textit{horizontal translations}:
\[
\includegraphics{../graphics/fptrans.pdf}
\]
We will not only insist that a frieze pattern always have
translational symmetry, but we will also insist that such a
translation is \textit{discrete}, meaning that it occurs in distinct
``hops'' of some minimal distance. So, for example, the while the
following patterns have minimal discrete translations, 
\[
2 examples (USE LETTERS)
\]
this pattern
\[
nonexample
\]
does not, and hence will not technically be considered a frieze
pattern. To be completely explicit: 
\begin{center}
\textbf{All frieze patterns have symmetry through some horizontal translation.}
\end{center}
\begin{dfn}\index{minimal translation cell}
A \textbf{minimal translation cell} is the smallest slice of a frieze pattern that will produce the entire frieze pattern through horizontal translations.
\end{dfn}

\begin{war}
The minimal translation cell of a frieze pattern is not unique! Consider
\[
image
\]
both
\[
2-egs
\]
are minimal translation cells.
\end{war} 



\subsection*{Horizontal Reflections}\index{horizontal reflections}

Frieze patterns can have symmetry though \textit{horizontal reflections}:
\[
\includegraphics{../graphics/fphoriz.pdf}
\]
Some frieze patterns have symmetry though horizontal reflections, while
others don't.
\begin{ques} Can you identify the frieze patterns below with symmetry though horizontal reflections?
\[
6 egs some with horiz/vert sym.
\]
\end{ques}

\begin{war}
Always remember: A horizontal reflection reflects across a vertical line!
\end{war}



\subsection*{Vertical Reflections}\index{vertical reflections}


Frieze patterns can have symmetry though \textit{vertical reflections}:
\[
\includegraphics{../graphics/fpvertical.pdf}
\]

\begin{ques} Can you identify the frieze patterns below with symmetry though vertical reflections?
\[
6 egs some with horiz/vert sym.
\]
\end{ques}

\begin{war}
Always remember: A vertical reflection reflects across a horizontal
line!
\end{war}




\subsection*{Glide Reflections}\index{glide reflections}

Frieze patterns can have symmetry though \textit{glide reflections}:
\[
\includegraphics{../graphics/fpglide.pdf}
\]

\begin{ques} Can you identify the frieze patterns below with symmetry though glide reflections?
\[
6 egs some with horiz/vert sym.
\]
\end{ques}

\begin{ques}
If a frieze pattern has symmetry through translations and vertical
reflections, must it have symmetry through glide reflections?
\end{ques}
\QM




\subsection*{Rotations}\index{rotations}

Finally, frieze patterns can have symmetry through $180^\circ$
rotations.
\[
\includegraphics{../graphics/fprot.pdf}
\]

\begin{ques}
Can you identify the frieze patterns below that have symmetry through $180^\circ$ rotations? 
\[
6 egs
\]
\end{ques}

\begin{ques}
Suppose you have a frieze pattern with symmetry though both glide
reflections and $180^\circ$ rotations. Must this pattern also have
symmetry through horizontal reflections?
\end{ques}
\QM



